<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[rainwarrior]]></name></author>
<updated>2014-05-21T10:03:06-07:00</updated>
<published>2014-05-21T10:03:06-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11261&amp;p=129008#p129008</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11261&amp;p=129008#p129008"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Additive and FM synth on the SPC700]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11261&amp;p=129008#p129008"><![CDATA[
FM synthesis implementations tend to work a lot better as phase modulation (see: any YM FM chip) than true frequency modulation. The two methods can produce identical output under ideal conditions, but true frequency modulation is much harder to implement in a stable way (i.e. sounds the same every time).<br /><br />If you're implementing a frequency modulation scheme on the SPC I would recommend resetting the waveform's phase at the start of the note, and try to keep the timings as consistent as possible. Very small timing variations can accumulate as big timbre differences in frequency modulation (something much easier to avoid with phase modulation, usually).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=5165">rainwarrior</a> — Wed May 21, 2014 10:03 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
